<DOC><DOCNO> AP890310-0018 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 0507EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-Sandamp;LTakeovers     03-10 0443</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Sandamp;L Takeovers,440</SECOND><HEAD>Forty-Five More Sandamp;Ls Taken Over</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. has takencontrol of 45 more failed savings and loans in eight states,bringing the total under the agency's control to 118 thriftinstitutions in 24 states.   As an interim step, President Bush is having the agency, whichregulates commercial banks, take over the sickest Sandamp;Ls, with thegoal of minimizing losses while Congress considers theadministration's proposal to rescue or close such institutions.   The FDIC plans to take control of about 100 more institutionswithin the next month. The agency is emphasizing that the Sandamp;Ls willremain open as usual and that all deposit accounts up to $100,000are fully protected by federal insurance.   The 45 institutions in Thursday's action, including 21 in Texasand nine in Colorado, had assets totaling $13.6 billion. Listed bystate, they are:</TEXT><NOTE>ALABAMA</NOTE><TEXT>   First Savings Bank of Alabama, Hamilton, and Phenix FederalSavings and Loan Association, Phenix City.</TEXT><HEAD>COLORADO</HEAD><TEXT>   Otero Savings and Loan Association, Colorado Springs; FirstFederal Savings and Loan Association of Colorado Springs; ColoradoSavings Association, Granby; Valley Federal Savings and LoanAssociation of Grand Junction; Mesa Federal Savings and LoanAssociation of Colorado, Grand Junction;   Modern Federal Savings and Loan Association, Grand Junction; SunSavings and Loan Association, Parker; Alpine Federal Savings andLoan Association, Steamboat Springs, and Rocky Mountain Savings andLoan Association, Woodland Park.</TEXT><HEAD>GEORGIA</HEAD><TEXT>   First Federal Savings and Loan Association, Atlanta, and FirstFederal Savings and Loan Association, Summerville.</TEXT><HEAD>MICHIGAN</HEAD><TEXT>   Peoples Savings Association, St. Joseph.</TEXT><HEAD>NEW MEXICO</HEAD><TEXT>   American Federal Savings and Loan Association, Albuquerque; SunCountry Savings Bank of New Mexico, Albuquerque, and Valley FederalSavings Bank, Roswell.</TEXT><HEAD>PENNSYLVANIA</HEAD><TEXT>   Liberty Bell Savings Association, Beaver Falls; Concord-LibertySavings and Loan Association, Monroeville, and Hill FinancialSavings Association, Red Hill.</TEXT><HEAD>TENNESSEE</HEAD><TEXT>   Germantown Trust Savings Bank, Germantown; Lincoln FederalSavings and Loan Association, Mount Carmel; Century Federal SavingsBank, Trenton, and United Guaranty Federal Savings Bank, Tullahoma.</TEXT><HEAD>TEXAS</HEAD><TEXT>   Western Gulf Savings and Loan Association, Bay City; Citizens ofTexas Savings and Loan Association, Baytown; Century Savings andLoan Association, Baytown; Continental Savings, Bellaire; TrinityValley Savings and Loan Association, Cleveland;   Southeastern Savings Association, Dayton; Bankers Savings andLoan Association, Galveston; Benjamin Franklin Savings Association,Houston; Village Savings, Houston; Commonwealth Savings Association,Houston;   Universal Savings Association, Houston; Ameriway Savings,Houston; Spring Branch Savings and Loan Association, Houston; FirstCapital Savings Association of Texas, Houston; Humble Savings andLoan Association, Humble;   Bayshore Savings Association, La Porte; American Savings and LoanAssociation of Brazoria, Lake Jackson; City Savings Association,League City; Liberty County Federal Savings and Loan Association,Liberty; Bancplus Savings Association, Pasadena, and First EquitySavings Association, Tomball.</TEXT></DOC>